passages.text: US stocks are trading lower Friday but endless summer (rally) August (for the S&P 500 as of Friday at 12:20 PM) as investors have been reacting this month to a rising probability that the Fed will cut rates following a weak jobs report at the start of the month (literally August 1st) and even as both business and consumer sentiment has shown signs of improvement throughout August.

The rally that started with the tariff pause on Apr- 9 got another boost through August, helped in part by more tariff news. While the incremental tariff rate on imported goods to the US looks to be coming in line with our economists' forecast (i.e., an incremental 15pp or more), news on tariffs on Japan and Europe this month avoided worst case scenarios. Europe, for example, saw its tariff come in at \(15\%\) across the board, implying that tariffs on autos will be 10pp lower than first announced (see Jari Stehn's Aug- 1 note, "European Views: As Good As It Gets" and Elsie Peng's Aug- 10 update, "Tariff Passthrough Update: More Underway Through June" for our latest view on how tariffs are being absorbed by the US economy).

Beyond tariffs, 2Q25 earnings season was also in focus over the course of August and the news was decidedly good as Ryan Hammond and team outlined in an Aug- 15 note, "2Q 2025 earnings season recap" (see also the charts of the month below). Prior to Retailer results in the last 2 weeks of August, aggregate S&P 500 earnings per share grew \(11\%\) year over year in 2Q25, exceeding the \(4\%\) consensus expectation. And earnings season was marked by widespread upward revisions to corporate guidance and analyst 2026 earnings estimates.

So, top- down fundamental news was better in August (especially when you also consider the potential corporate stimulus effects embedded in the budget bill passed in early July). And bottoms- up news was significantly better than expected (2Q EPS up \(11\%\) vs 4.5% forecast). Looking through stocks through this earnings lens, it's not at all surprising to see that the S&P 500 gained more ground in the month.

So why doesn't it feel as good as it looks? As always, the answer lies in the details. Forward tailwinds for corporate earnings are well telegraphed: upward 2Q earnings revisions, tax cuts embedded in the budget bill, the prospect for the Fed to cut rates

(see David Mericle's Jackson Hole speech postview note, "USA: Powell Says Baseline Outlook and Shifting Risks 'May Warrant Adjusting Our Policy Stance'") and technology advancements continue to fuel an AI spending binge (see Eric Sheridan's Aug- 20 note, "Internet: Recapping Takeaways & Debates; Focus Stocks Going Forward"). But up against these well- telegraphed tailwinds are a series of headwinds and 'red flags' that are still restraining sentiment — and may provide the foundation of a 'wall of worry' necessary for stocks to climb even higher from here.
Risks we are monitoring.

1. Growth. Jan Hatzius sees a path for the Fed to restart its rate cutting cycle at its September meeting at least partly because the labor market is showing signs of slowing as he detailed in the Aug-4 Global Views, "On Course for Cuts." The July Payrolls report included downward revisions to prior months' data that suggest the labor market has been subpar for quite some time now. And our economists estimate that underlying job growth has plummeted to \(\sim 25k\) jobs per month from over 200k to start the year (see chart of the month below).

2. Inflation. So far, CPI and PCE inflation have remained constrained even in the face of much higher tariff burdens for importers. But July wholesale inflation — PPI — came in much higher than expected, partly reflecting the tariff impulse (see "USA: PPI Well Above Expectations in July"). And July Core PCE inflation reported on Friday Aug-29 was in-line with expectations, but still elevated at \(+0.27\%\) mom, \(+2.88\%\) yoy, driven entirely by services inflation as goods inflation remains anemic despite the introduction of new tariffs (see "USA: Core PCE in Line With Expectations; Goods Trade Deficit Widens; Lowering Q3 GDP Tracking to \(1.6\%\) ").

3. The Fed. The consensus view is for the Fed to cut rates at its September meeting (see our economists' notes above). But the notion of Fed independence came under greater scrutiny in August on the back of statements and actions taken by the Trump Administration. Allison Nathan explored just what Fed Independence means for monetary policy, the economy and markets back on May-15 in "Top of Mind: Fed independence: how concerning?" For markets, a less independent Fed could dent the appeal of the Dollar and US Treasuries, while boosting Gold. For insights on these three asset classes, click into three recent notes: Ken Ho's Aug-27 note, "De-Dollarization A Gradual Path For Asia Credit Investors;" George Cole's Aug-22 update, "Global Rates Trader: Cutting Through Mixed Messages;" and Lina Thomas' Aug-17 deep dive, "Gold Market Primer").

4. AI efficacy. The AI infrastructure investment cycle continued unabated through July and likely through the summer as our analysts highlighted in a series of notes on the hyperscalers (see Sheridan's note above and Kash Rangan's Jul-31 update, "MSFT: The AI Halo Effect Ripples up the Stack - F4Q25 Earnings" and charts of the month below). But the prospect for this huge increase in compute power to translate into tangible applications that change peoples lives remains somewhat elusive. Gabriela Borges and Rangan highlighted how the underperformance in software stocks over concerns that AI will replace the need for legacy software applications is overdone in "Software GenAI Part XII: Updated thoughts on the 'Death of Software' bear case." And earlier in the summer, Jim Covello and Sheridan dove into how AI may

meaningfully (or not) disrupt existing profit pools, providing visibility on a path to a return on all of this investment in "Analyzing the Impact of AI on Industry Profit Pools - Part I (Advertising Case Study)." Bottom- line: the path to returns may be long, and in the meantime the cost of clear the way is very expensive and profits have so far been concentrated. a single company: NVDA (see also Jim Schneider's postview on NVDA results. NVDA: Blue quarter relative to elevated expectations; we see meaningful- side heading into 2026").

5. Irrational exuberance. Fed Chair Alan Greenspan coined this phrase back in late 1996, capturing his concerns around inflated asset valuations in the wake of a sharp rally in stocks that took place following a steady Fed funds rate hiking cycle that ended in mid-1995. Fast forward to today, and we are seeing similar characteristics in some corners of the market just before what many expect will be a sustained Fed funds rate cutting cycle re-starting at the September FOMC meeting (see Mericle's Aug-17 note, "Slower Job Growth Makes the Case for a Cut"). David Kostin points out in the Aug-22 "US Kickstart" that the S&P 500 is now trading at 23X NTM earnings estimates. Ben Snider also highlighted in a Jul-24 note, "Speculative trading activity adds fuel to narrow-breadth short squeeze," how a spike in trading activity in unprofitable stocks, penny stocks, and stocks with elevated EV/sales multiples pushed our Speculative Trading Indicator (STI) to its highest level outside of 1998-2001 and 2020-2021 (both periods that were soon followed by Tech stock crashes).

Against all of this backdrop — the VIX is actually sitting near ytd lows at 15.5 — Christian Mueller Glissmann cautions that risk/reward now skews to the downside in the Aug- 14 note, "Goldilocks vs. the Bears — Mixed Equity Asymmetry Compared to Historical Low Vol Regimes." Low vol coming at the same time as we are seeing a combination of elevated equity valuations and a weakening business cycle makes for an elevated probability of an equity drawdown. And the valuation stretch doesn't just apply to stocks. Lotfi Karoui advocates keeping some downside protection in Credit portfolios given stretched valuations in the Aug-21 Global Credit update, "Solid foundations, sky-high valuations."

What about that wall of worry? A wall of worry is easier to climb when an investor is not too long that wall's foundation (stocks). And Ryan Hammond and Ben Snider updated our investor positioning trackers in two notes in last August "Hedge Fund Trend Monitor: Not out of the woods yet" and "Mutual Fundamentals: Despite elevated return dispersion, mutual funds struggle to keep pace with rising benchmark." The good news: Short interest for the median S&P 500 stock represents 2.3% of float, near the highest level since 2019. And our Hedge Fund Crowding Index remains near record highs and market breadth registers one of the narrowest levels in recent decades, a dynamic that has often preceded short squeezes in the past.

This summer was a tail of three trends: (1) signs of slowing in the broader economy (see Jan Hatzius' Aug- 4 Global Views, "On Course for Cuts"); (2) renewed evidence that AI infrastructure spending remains robust; and (3) signs of resilience if not acceleration

in corporate earnings. The AI investment cycle (see Dom Wilson's Aug- 18 note, "Easing in Season") is likely supporting corporate earnings resilience, of course, but we also saw a broadening of upside earnings surprises in 2Q results, as David Kostin pointed out in the Aug- 15 "US Kickstart," which suggests that US earnings power extends beyond just AI. Whether markets succumb to a slowing economy or continue to rally into the momentum of fortress Corporate America may be the question for fall (see charts below for an illustration of these conflicting signs).

We also host our 32nd Annual Global Retailing Conference in New York next week, providing a great opportunity to check in on the consumer and back- to- school activity ("click here for the agenda").

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FC and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
